Class VariableFact

java.lang.Object

public class VariableFact
extends Fact

The variable fact is a fact that contains one or more variables.

Like the fact, it has columns for each element of the fact, but it also has a parallel array marking whether or not each column is a variable.

canMapVariables

public boolean canMapVariables(Expression other)
Description copied from class: Expression
Can this expression be mapped to the other expression? An expression can be mapped to another expression if and only if there is a unifier from the one to the other that only makes variable assignments.

Note that this relationship is not symmetric: one expression can be mapped to another expression, despite that second relation not mapping to the first.

Specified by:
canMapVariables in class Expression
Parameters:
other - The expression with which to test mapping.
Returns:
True if this can be mapped to other.

fromList

public static Fact fromList(GdlList list)
Construct a variable fact from a GdlList. Note that the list must be a list of atoms, in other words, there cannot be any nested lists. The fact is constructed by taking the first element of the list as the fact's relation name, and every subsequent element as a column. If an atom is found to be a variable, then that column is marked as a variable.

Parameters:
list - The list to build the fact from.
Returns:
A variable fact representing the data from the list.
Throws:
java.lang.IllegalAccessException - when the passed list is not a list of atoms.
See Also:
GdlList
